vectorData.altText: 22. The ___________ glands are associated with the terminus of the female urethra.

In the female, the urethra extends from the internal urethral orifice at the neck of the bladder, through the pelvic floor, to open into the vestibule at the external urethral orifice. As the urethra passes through the pelvic floor it is surrounded by the striated, voluntary external urethral sphincter, located in the deep perineal pouch. The labia minora form the borders of the vestibule, the space into which the urethra and vagina open. The female urethra is 4 cm long, significantly shorter than the male urethra. The urethra lies anterior to the vagina and the two are joined by CT. The para-urethral (Skene’s) glands are paired mucus-secreting glands that open into the terminal urethra.
That’s right! The paraurethral glands secrete mucus into the terminal urethra of the female.
